# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maritime-timeline
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The **Third Spanish Armada**, also known as the **Spanish Armada of 1597**, was involved in a major naval event that took place between 18 October and 15 November 1597 as part of the Anglo–Spanish War.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The attack of the armada, which was the third attempt by Spain to invade or raid the British Isles during the war, was ordered by King Philip II of Spain in revenge for the English attack on Cádiz following the failure of the 2nd Spanish Armada the previous year due to a storm.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Armada was executed by the Adelantado Martín de Padilla, which had the same objective as the second armada – the support of the Irish rebels in rebellion against the English crown.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] It was also an opportunity to intercept and destroy the English fleet under Robert Devereux the 2nd Earl of Essex as it returned from the failed Azores expedition.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The objective of landing in Ireland changed due to conflicting ideals - instead the armada was to capture either the important port of Falmouth or Milford Haven and use those places as a base for invasion.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] With 140 ships and 14,000 soldiers and sailors the Spanish set out in October 1597 and arrived in the English Channel.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] As they approached near the Lizard they were dispersed by a storm which scattered their fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Even so, some ships did push on and even landed troops on the English and Welsh coasts.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The returning English fleet, which had been scattered by the same storm, were unaware that the Spanish had come to intercept them, and had arrived safely in England with the loss of only one ship.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Padilla realising his fleet was unable to make full landfall, finally ordered a retreat back to Spain.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The returning English ships captured a number of Spanish ships, from which valuable information was obtained about the Armada.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Panic in England then ensued, partly because the English fleet had been out to sea with the English coast virtually undefended.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This caused the relationship between Queen Elizabeth I of England and the Earl of Essex to deteriorate further and Charles Howard, the 1st Earl of Nottingham, took over from Essex as commander of the English fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Howard immediately sent the fleet out to hunt the Spanish Any remaining Spanish ships were rounded up and captured along with their soldiers and crew, most of whom had arrived back at port.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Philip took much of the blame for the failure by the Armada commanders, particularly Padilla.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Armada was the last of its kind that the Spanish would execute under Philip II before his death.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The war with Spain and England had been going on for nearly twelve years and both sides had achieved little in their goals.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The result of the intervention of Philip II in the religious war in France in support of the Catholic League, meant that the Spanish had established coastal garrisons along the French and Flemish coast by the 1580s.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] These bases had a huge strategic value because they allowed England to be threatened by the Spanish fleet and troops.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Meanwhile, England also intervened in France, but in support of King Henry IV of France, by the Treaty of Greenwich in 1591.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spaniards had captured Calais in 1596 which meant that an invasion of England could be more achievable.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] As a result, after desperate French demands to keep her from signing peace with Spain, the English signed the Triple Alliance with the Dutch Republic and France.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] England had sent an armada the next year under the Earl of Essex and Charles Howard to Cádiz which was captured and sacked.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] An angered Philip soon after took into consideration the defence of the peninsula.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In a wave of revenge after the defeat at Cádiz, Philip II sent out orders for a large armada to do the same to England by way of taking the French port of Brest.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Just after they set off however the fleet was obliterated in autumn storms off Cape Finisterre causing severe losses in ships (including a few galleons known as the Apostles), men, supplies, and money.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The cost was ruinous; the two ships carrying the pay-chests disappeared below the waves.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish King not to be disheartened ordered another invasion despite the Cortes Generales claiming funds would not be available in time.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] As a result, the Cortes was asked to be dissolved by Philip and a financial crisis loomed.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Cádiz defeat, the failure of the Armada, as well as the war in France and the Netherlands that year meant that Philip's nation went into bankruptcy; the third of his reign.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Adding to the King's and Spain's woes, a poor harvest began to take effect in the country and thousands were affected.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This caused many to protest as they were unable to pay their taxes.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The formation of the Triple Alliance meant that grain from abroad was harder to obtain.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Despite this, the fleet albeit with great difficulty was mustered and men were pressed into service across the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] There was a heavy reliance on the Italian holdings to make up the losses from the previous year's failed armada as well as funds and supplies.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Pedro Lopez de Soto, of Castile, the Secretary of the Adelantado, was to command the fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The whole force, according to Lopez de Soto's estimate was huge in terms of men, ships, and supplies.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The primary original objective was Ireland to support the rise of the rebels under Hugh O'Neill, Earl of Tyrone, but the senior Spanish commanders wanted to attack England instead.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish King however intervened and ordered an attack on Brest to divert troops from the garrisons in the Low Countries.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] When news came however that the English had sailed in force again under Essex, and were first on the coasts of the Peninsula, and then cruising round the Azores to capture the treasure fleets, there was shock at the Spanish court.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This news would put difficulties which Philip's system had created for himself.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The King was swept away by a passion for revenge so much so he resolved to carry out his objective as swiftly as possible even at the expense of preparation.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] At A Coruña the fleet was assembled under the command of Juan del Aguila as field master general, and Martín de Padilla the Adelantado, commander of the invading troops.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The plan had now switched from Ireland with the objective of the Port of Falmouth in Cornwall.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish were to hold the town and port and force Elizabeth into a peace or hoping to attract the Catholic followers and rise up in support.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] It was estimated that this would be far larger than that of the 1588 invasion attempt.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The troopships were to take Falmouth, while the warships would also intercept and destroy Essex's returning fleet from the Azores.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The other target as a failsafe as well as a strategic diversion was Milford Haven in Wales, a good landing ground from which Henry VII had landed his men to defeat King Richard III in 1485.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] A Spanish observer had noted that Milford contained many Welsh Catholics who were hostile to the English.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The true intentions of the Armada, however, were confusing to the captains and officers, as they didn't really know whether this was an invasion, a raid, or a naval interception.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] For fear of spies and deserters in the fleet, only the high command knew, and they were taking no chances.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] All would be revealed only as they approached the English Channel.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The taking and holding of Falmouth or Milford was a strategy the Spanish would use to hold a piece of England in retaliation for the seizure of Cádiz.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In turn this would be used as a bargaining chip to force English troops to withdraw from the continent, both in France and the United Provinces.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] If they did not, then the captured places would also be used as a forward base for the harassment of English and Dutch trade.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In all 108 ships were at A Coruña, most others would join after departing from other ports.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] By 1 October the fleet consisted of 136 ships of 34,080 tons, of these were 44 royal galleons, of an aggregate tonnage of 12,686 tons; 16 merchantmen, of 5880 tons, 52 German and Flemish hulks for stores, of 15,514 tons, and 24 caravels, pinnaces, and barks.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] There were 8,634 soldiers, 4,000 sailors, a total of 12,634 men and 300 horses.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In this squadron of 32 Andalusia troopships included Carlos de Amésquita who had raided Cornwall two years earlier.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] These carried the elite Spanish military units known as tercios, many were from the Spanish domains in Italy such as Naples and Lombardy and had rarely been beaten in battle.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish Armada of 1597, as incomplete as it was, put to sea from A Coruña on 18 October.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] However, with a military force very different from that foreshadowed by Lopez de Soto's estimate.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Armada left A Coruña and Ferrol after which a fleet under Admiral Diego Brochero was to meet another from Blavet in Brittany (under Spanish rule) with a thousand men under Pedro de Zubiaur.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Zubiaur joined them for a council of war which was made to settle the final details of the landing.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] After three days of sailing in good weather, the fleet arrived in the Channel, after advancing towards the English coast without opposition.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] As they sailed on, an English bark was intercepted and sunk, with what was left of the crew being taken prisoner.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Events changed otherwise as the weather turned.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] An easterly wind turned into a gale and for a few days the storm would continue.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This time however there were no catastrophic results such as those of 1588 and the Spanish were more organised in ship-to-ship communication.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] At first, the Adelantado tried to ride out the storm in the hope that the weather would relent.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] But at dawn the next day, the winds only intensified.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] For three days the storm blew, Spanish ship losses increased, the *San Lucas* ran aground off the Lizard casting away their horses and mules.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The galleon carrying Don Pedro Guevera – General of artillery - caught fire, blew up in a tremendous explosion, and was never seen again.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Another large vessel with siege equipment and flammables (for burning English ships in Falmouth) also suffered a catastrophic explosion which took with her a chartered French ship full of soldiers.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Only one of the large galleons sank, the *San Bartolomé*, when it was dashed on rocks near the Isles of Scilly.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In the *San Pedro*, Brochero had to drop out of the station to a Biscay port as the ship was so badly damaged, but he was put to sea again in a flyboat and rejoined the armada.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] He attempted to rally them in one last effort to make a landing at Milford Haven, Waterford, Cork or Brest.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] On the night of 25 October, seeing that the currents were unrelenting he reluctantly ordered the remaining ships to start to part company and to scatter, each one thinking of their own safety.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] One Spanish ship dismasted by the storm was captured off the Scilly Isles by an English pinnace.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Even though it sank on its way to Penzance, the prisoners, including its captain, master, and purser, were brought in and sent to Falmouth.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Here the English captain reported that the Spanish fleet was some thirty leagues off the Scilly Isles.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In addition the Spanish prisoners had with them letters and plans on their rendezvous at Falmouth.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This was the first indication of presence of the Armada off the Cornish shores and immediately the Privy Council met.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] However, the evidence from only one ship was not enough.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Also, the English fleet had not yet arrived.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They could only send orders, pay, and supplies to the fleet in hope that it would return in time.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The few ships in the area, including the *Vanguard*, were immediately sent.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Queen's cousin, the Earl of Ormond, was given command of all military forces in Ireland in case the Spanish ships decided on landfall there.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Elizabeth herself was told of the Spanish fleet on 26 October, two days after opening Parliament.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The storm had a huge effect on the Spanish fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Several ships were swept up much further north of Cornwall to the Welsh coast.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish captains then rendezvoused as instructed.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Three Spanish ships came near Pembrokeshire and headed towards Milford Haven, the secondary objective.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The forty-ton caravel *Nuestra Senora Buenviage* was driven ashore by the storm in Milford Haven, where she was captured and then plundered.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] She had gold and silver aboard, and the Welsh militia fought over it, with a man wounded.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Another vessel was beached near Aberdyfi on 26 October, the 120-ton *Bear of Amsterdam*.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Poor navigation meant that she had missed Milford Haven but had sailed via the Dyfi Estuary instead.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They landed men ashore but were ambushed by the Merionethshire Militia having lost two killed and four captured.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They then retreated back to their ship but were unable to leave due to lack of wind.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Off Caldey Island, a Spanish treasure ship from Dunkirk had run aground, but disorder among the locals allowed the ship to escape.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In Cornwall a Spanish force landed 700 elite soldiers on a beach in one of the creeks off the Helford River near Falmouth, and dug in, waiting for reinforcements.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] English militia began to arrive in large numbers (although poorly armed), but the Spanish fleet was still hopelessly dispersed.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] With no hope of reinforcement, the Spanish troops re-embarked in the dark, after just two days ashore.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The rumours caused confusion and as a result Plymouth and the surrounding area were put on alert.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Sir Ferdinand Gorges, the Governor of the Fort at Plymouth, put a 500-man guard on the town and a pinnace was sent out to feedback sightings of the Spanish fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Gorges was fed reports of the landings in Cornwall and Wales and sightings of Spanish ships.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] He immediately sent the information to parliament and the Queen in London in the quickest possible time.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] An excited panic set in motion across much of England and Wales.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Troops were being recalled from Amiens in France (it had recently been captured by the Anglo-French force the previous month) and for the mobilization of troops in the West Country.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Charles Blount, the 8th Baron Mountjoy, was put in command of the English land forces while the few galleons from Chatham were sent to the Cornish and Devon coasts.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Although dispersed by a storm they reached Falmouth a few days later, but on arrival had not seen any Spanish ships.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] At the same time some of the Spanish ships were still a presence off the coast of England, milling about in confusion without being able to make any harbour.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Eventually with a wind astern, the order was given by Brochero to head back to Spain and they sailed back in disorder to A Coruña.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] On 23 October the day after the Spanish had ordered a dispersal, leading elements of the English fleet had started to return to Falmouth, Plymouth, and Dartmouth but amazingly had completely missed the retreating Spanish fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] At one point both fleets English and Spanish were on converging lines with one another.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Essex on arrival soon learned from Mountjoy of the situation and both were surprised as each other as to how the English fleet had missed the Spanish.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Essex immediately wrote letters to parliament and the Queen in order to salvage the situation.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Initially he was invested by the Queen with full powers sent down to him.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The channel squadron was ordered to join his flag.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The government soon after were impressed by his actions and understandings of the intentions of the Spanish fleet: the capture of Falmouth or Milford Haven or the interception of the English fleet from the Azores.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] However soon after in one spirited letter by the Queen he was given a back hand by her for his failings in the Azores and the addition of England having been left unguarded.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Essex immediately went to Court to explain his actions but was to be met by an icy disapproval from the Queen.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] After which he went home to Wanstead to nurse his misery.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Howard of Effingham in Essex's absence was given the command of the fleet to make sure the threat was alleviated.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] A few days later the last of the English had arrived which included Vice Admiral of the fleet Sir Walter Raleigh in the galleon *Warspite* under commander Sir Arthur Gorges who was swept up round to St Ives.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] *Warspite* was heading into the port for repairs but soon sighted a Spanish bark and a pinnace.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Gorges intercepted them and after a very brief action captured them both along with the soldiers and crew.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Juan Triego, the captain of the pinnace, was interrogated by Gorges and Raleigh.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] He was forced to give away Spanish plans and dispositions.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They also learnt that the Spanish had previously gathered intelligence on the English coast a year before.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Perez, the captain of the bark, also confirmed the same information.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] All the other prisoner officers and captains both from St Ives and Milford Haven were interrogated.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Detailed information of the strength and organisation of the fleet was obtained.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Its formidable size for the first time was clearly understood.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish fleet had come as close as ten leagues from The Lizard, although the danger at this time was still real.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Reports from returning English ships from the Azores voyage had seen Spanish ships albeit at long range.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Raleigh having been made Lieutenant General went overland from St Ives and joined Howard in Plymouth.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They hurriedly put to sea a small fleet (many of the crew were exhausted from the Azores cruise) to pursue the Spanish.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Mountjoy took command on land organising the troops and militia of Plymouth and the surrounding area, and would soon be reinforced by troops from the Low Countries.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] By the time the English had put to sea the lead elements of the Spanish had already arrived safely at A Coruña although the English knew nothing of this.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The English scouted as far as the Bay of Biscay even heading to Western French ports for any evidence of Spanish arrivals.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] On the 30th a warship under the command of Captain Bowden from Howard's fleet had intercepted and captured a ship from the Spanish fleet off Cape Finisterre.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The prize was a flyboat carrying an army captain and 40 soldiers besides sailors, and Bowden had boarded and taken her with a crew of only 28 men and boys.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The captain and officers were again interrogated and the same evidence of the Spanish invasion was given, but the news this time was that the captain had only seen one of his cohorts, heading some 30 leagues to the coast of Spain.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Further evidence of the Spanish retreat was given by Sir George Carew in the *Adventure* who after a storm had driven his squadron further south.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] He saw and immediately pursued eleven ships bearing the flag of Castile hastening back home to Spain.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish ships were too far ahead to be intercepted however so Carew joined Howard with the main fleet to give the news.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] These two reports meant that the invasion was effectively over; Howard and Raleigh sent the fleet back to Plymouth to report the news to Parliament and court.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The only Spanish ship in the area left from the Armada; the 120-ton *Bear of Amsterdam* was still at Aberdyfi.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] After ten days because of a lack of wind the *Bear of Amsterdam* could not be boarded by the militia as there were no suitable boats.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] An attempt to burn the ship was thwarted by the wind and the *Bear of Amsterdam* eventually left.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] She was driven around the Cornish peninsula and swept up the channel by an easterly gale suffering some damage.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Hoping to see the Spanish already at Falmouth, the ship was captured not far off from there on 10 November by a waiting English squadron.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] She was led into Dartmouth with 70 Spaniards taken prisoner, and this being the last ship from the Armada to be captured.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] By the middle of November it was clear that the Spanish Armada invasion had obviously failed and some floating remains of Spanish ships were coming ashore on the English coast.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The fleet, militias, and troops were kept on alert but it was realized that the danger had passed and were thus disbanded for winter quarters.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Troops that had arrived from the continent either returned to Holland or France once the situation had abated.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Overall seven ships and around 15 other vessels were sunk.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Six Spanish ships in total from the armada were captured by the English all over the South West of England and West Wales.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Only one large galleon was lost, while a merchant hulk was captured by the French in which its 300 crew were imprisoned.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In all between 1,500 and 2,000 troops, sailors, and civilians were lost, captured, or were sick to disease.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] A muster on 21 November put the number of ships at A Coruña at 108 vessels with many in need of repairs, while the entire fleet required new provisions, especially victuals.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] With these losses, the failure of the campaign ended any hope of making an attack for the remainder of the year.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In addition the core of the English Catholics did not rise up in rebellion even when the Spanish fleet offshore was known to them, in fact many had even spoken out in support of fighting them.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] King Philip according to the Spanish commanders had more trust in God than in preparation.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish king was distraught by the news and he knew there was no possibility a third attack by an armada could be attempted.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] He afterwards fell ill, went into a palsy, and shut himself away in his palace.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Bonfires and processions all over Spain were lit in the hope of his health returning.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Before he had been taken ill, Philip had decided that he only wanted peace.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] His health did not improve and he resultingly died the following year.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] For the English and in particular Queen Elizabeth it was more about luck as to how England had been saved.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] However she was displeased with Essex for the fact that the Azores expedition was a failure as well as leaving England's coastline defenceless.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The English had obtained vital information from the captured Spanish ships and prisoners.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They were able to learn what was happening, including the objectives and overall strategy of the Spanish Armada as a whole within a few days, whilst the ships were off the English and Welsh coasts.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Howard on his return was rewarded soon after by the Queen and was created Earl of Nottingham.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Lessons were learned however, in particular at Falmouth, where Mountjoy's consultant military engineer Paul Ivey was responsible for strengthening the castles at St Mawes and Pendennis.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] It was put into immediate effect – information from prisoners claimed that an invasion would be attempted the following summer but only if the taking of Falmouth or Milford had succeeded.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This was confirmed by an English spy in Spain who commented on the Spanish confusion and misfortune in the aftermath but "bragged about what they would do next Spring".
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Plymouth and Milford Haven's defences were also improved as well as militia units trained in the art of war.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In all, two companies of English foot soldiers from the Low countries had been in place in Cornwall.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] English troops from France on standby returned there to fight with Henry IV in Brittany at the closing of the Franco-Spanish war before the Peace of Vervins was signed.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The Spanish would never again try sending a large naval armada directed at England.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The cost had almost been ruinous to Spain and nearly bankrupted the country's finance again.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] It was not as bad as the previous years failure however since gold and silver bullion was still arriving in numbers from the Americas.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The insurmountable debt rose and soon after the campaign there was a further arrangement to clear it.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The new King Philip III in 1598 would be more cautious.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Under the advisement of Don Francisco Gómez de Sandoval, 1st Duke of Lerma would try one more attempt.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The final Armada was sent in 1601 in support of Irish clans under Hugh O'Neill against English rule.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] Although smaller -33 ships with 4,500 men, the Armada led by Juan del Águila and Pedro de Zubiaur succeeded in landing, after a severe storm again nearly put paid to the operation.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] This venture too however ended in disaster when the entire Spanish force capitulated after their defeat at the Battle of Kinsale.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] The failure of the armadas thus ceded the naval initiative to England who were still able to launch expeditions to Spain without much hindrance.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] For the first time in English naval history, effective offshore blockades were launched with expeditions such as one led by William Monson and Richard Leveson most notably off Sesimbra in 1602.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] They could also defend the Channel when some months later a Spanish fleet of Galleys was defeated by an Anglo-Dutch force.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] It was only until peace was settled that Spain could spare any harm on its colonies and its merchant ships from England's *seas dogs*.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] In 1953 during the coronation of Queen Elizabeth II, in Aberdyfi a local ship was fitted out to represent the Spanish caravel *The Bear of Amsterdam*.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] She was moored mid-river and set on fire.
[src:maritime-timeline/3rd-spanish-armada] A restaurant in the same town is also named after the ship.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:maritime-timeline/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:maritime-timeline/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The **Achaemenid navy** (Old Persian: 𐎴𐎠𐎺 *nāva*) was the principal naval force of the Achaemenid Empire which existed between 525 BC and 330 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] In Old Persian, the written language of Achaemenid inscriptions, the word used to refer to the 'navy' or 'fleet' was "*nāva*", a noun in plural feminine nominative form.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] It is of the same root of Indo-European for words such as "navy" and "navigate".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] In modern usage of Persian language, the word has retained its form and meaning (lit.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] No relevant primary documents have been found about it, nor have any ruins of Persian naval installations or remains of ships been excavated.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] While independent Persian tradition is lost, all we know about the Achaemenid navy is recorded by ancient Greek historians like Herodotus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Scholars categorize the record of operation of the navy to two distinct periods from 525 to 479, and from 479 to 330 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Cambyses founded the navy for conquest of Egypt in the Battle of Pelusium.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] After him, Darius I deployed the navy to strengthen dominance over the coast of Asia Minor, as well as its adjacent islands.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] During reign of Darius, Persians captured Samos (c.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] 517 BC), conquered Thrace, waged war on Scythia (c.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] 512 BC), and suppressed rebellions started in 500 BC, leading to the Battle of Lade (494 BC).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The navy had lost its presence in the Aegean Sea, and its strength was reduced.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] 468 BC), the Persians were defeated and lost 200 ships according to the account of Thucydides.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The next significant defeat occurred in c.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] 450 BC, when they lost a war in Cyprus (near modern-day Larnaca).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The creation the organization, infrastructure, and financial basis of the Achaemenid navy is attributed to Darius I.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The coasts of Phoenicia, as well as Cyprus and Cilicia, always played a strategic role in the Achaemenid navy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Strabo and Herodotus mentioned two central bases for the navy: one in Cilicia and the other in Kyme–Phocaea (both located in modern-day Turkey).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Centers that trained crew for vessels were isolated from the central bases.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The Cilician base was heavily guarded by a large number of troops, whose payments were financed by the local tributes in that satrapy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] It is likely that Acco served as the third main base.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] According to Kaveh Farrokh, the first naval headquarters that hosted high command of the navy was located along the Shatt al-Arab, where it leads to the Persian Gulf (located in the modern-day Khuzestan Province of Iran).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] However, Cilicia was the main base and was always ready for deployment because unlike Shatt al-Arab, it was intended for power projection.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Smaller squadrons were stationed elsewhere, like those of Sidon and Halicarnassus, as well as Samos.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] An important base was a shipyard located at Tripolis, where Lebanese timber were nearby.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The Nile valley also served as a strategic base of operation, when Egypt was a satrapy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid settlements like Bahrain, Oman, Yemen and the Indian subcontinent were regular destinations for naval ships.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] It is thought likely that bases existed in Abdera and Myus, though this is uncertain.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces had an active presence in the Black Sea, the Aegean Sea, the Mediterranean Sea and the Persian Gulf among others.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] They operated patrols in river or littoral environments like Shatt al-Arab and Euphrates in Mesopotamia, Nile in Egypt and Sind in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The command hierarchy of the navy is not certain, but Greek sources indicate that high commanders were selected from the imperial aristocracy.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] There are reports of commanders of ships, and commanding officers of fleets with various non-Persians backgrounds, such as those of Carians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Commanders of Greek origin are also reported to have served in the navy, including even one Athenian.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Almost nothing is known about sailors of lower rank.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] In the wake of creating the navy, Persians hired Phoenician rowers and sailors, but later recruited from other subject peoples.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The marines standing in the forces were either Persians, Medes, or Scythians.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The servicemen were probably employed with full payment, because lengthy deployments imposed a drastic change to their communities especially if it included one or two harvests.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The first Achaemenid naval vessels, which were built at Phoenician shipyards, measured 40 meters (130 ft) in length and 6 meters (20 ft) width, and were capable of carrying 300 troops at best.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] According to Christopher Tuplin, Cypriot ships "appear a significant element in Persian fleets on various occasions".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The Persians were the first nation to use triremes in significant numbers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The first large trireme was commissioned by Cambyses.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] By 490 BC, the backbone of the fleet was consisted of triremes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Some triremes were modified as troopers, as well as some for carrying horses and supplies or building bridges.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Persian triremes differed from those of the Greek, and used Phoenician design.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The third level of rowers in Greek vessels was accommodated by adding a outrigger, but the Persians added to the height of the compartment instead.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] They reportedly were 110 feet (34 m) to 120 feet (37 m) long and had a beam of 15 feet (4.6 m).
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The ships were most likely capable of reaching 12 knots (22 km/h) under good sailing conditions.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] They could reach full speed in 30 seconds from a dead stop.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Equipped with one mast with square sail, the triremes had rudders made up of two bladed oars, one on each side of stern, united by a crossbar.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The ram was made out of bronze, and was long and tapered to a single point.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The metal rams were designed to slice into the hulls of enemy ships after an impact.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Equipment included grappling hooks (used to catch and halt enemy ships) and two mangonels, the latter throwing stones or flammable projectiles.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] A typical Persian trireme is reported to have had 170 rowers, with the upper file carrying 62, and the middle and lower files each 54.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] In addition to the rowers, other personnel aboard triremes included 14 marines and some spare rowers and oars in case they were needed.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] In 480 BC, each trireme carried 200 men and 30 marines, according to Herodotus.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Triremes were too crowded to store their own supplies, and relied on support vessels for food and water.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] It was normal for the crew to disembark in the evening for eating and sleep.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid navy later used more advanced vessels like quinqueremes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Other types of vessel in the fleet were triaconters, penteconters and light boats.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Smaller vessels used for river patrols could carry a maximum of 100–200 troops.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The navy operated a large number of vessels used to carry food and other supplies, which commonly had a displacement of 100 to 150 tons, at the time they invaded Egypt in 373 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Ships capable of carrying 350 to 500 tons were also used in significant numbers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] They also had horse transporters (*hippagogoi*) specifically built for this purpose, that could easily carry 30 horses.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Persian horse transport ships were good sailing ships that took advantage of the favorable winds, according to Anthony J.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Papalas, who adds they were probably designed to match the speed of a trireme.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] It is probable that horse transports were galleys with a shallow draft, that allowed horses get off in the waters and embark via a ramp.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenids are known to have used vessels for connecting the banks of rivers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The bridges were built by joining vessels to one another and lashing them together, to erect a roadway with planks.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon reports such bridges, one made using 37 boats on Tigris, and another using seven on Maeander.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] During its early years under Cambyses, the Achaemenid navy is assumed to possess about 300 triremes, which was equal to the sum of the fleet of Egypt and its ally Polycrates of Samos.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] This number was later doubled, with 600 triremes mentioned in 494 and 490 BC.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The initial set-up of the navy (300 triremes) may have had up to 51,000 rowers and thousands of sailors and marines.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The original number of vessels in the fleet was eventually quadrupled, according to Greek sources.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus' account of naval forces under Xerxes I, put the number of warships in service at 1,207, in addition to 3,000 transport ships.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Contemporary academic estimates range from 500 to 1,000 vessels, according to Matt Waters.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Scholars maintain that this number included large numbers of reserve ships, and the navy had not enough full oar crews to operate them all.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus also states that Persians arrived for the Battle of Marathon (490 BC) with 600 triremes and some horse transport vessels.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Though the number is rejected by some academics, Anthony J.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Papalas states that evidence does support this report.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Considering that each ship had an average of 50 oarsmen (the absolute minimum for a trireme) and 10 to 20 seamen and marines were also aboard, the navy compromised 36,000 to 42,000 men, at least.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] After the Battle of Salamis (480 BC), the fleet began to decline and never regained its peak numbers.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The largest figure estimated after 404 BC is 400 triremes.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The number was still equal to, if not more than, the fleets of the Athenian alliance.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon wrote in *Anabasis*, "his (Cyrus the Younger) ensign was a golden eagle with outspread wings mounted upon a long shaft and this continues even unto this day as the ensign of the Persian king".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] While there is not much to confirm this, some scholars maintain that *Alexander Mosaic* contained a depiction of the standard (on the part which is now damaged), head of a bird in yellow on a red cloth.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] There is also a square plaque found at Apadana in plain, and it is quite possible that it shows the eagle.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenid navy was the first true "imperial navy" that appeared in history.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] Persians are also credited for establishing the 'trireme navy' as the naval standard of their time.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The establishment of the Achaemenid navy set the basis of Iranian naval engineering, as well as "a powerful Persian maritime tradition that remained in the region until the arrival of the British East India Company and the Royal Navy by the mid-19th century AD".
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces affected the coastal subjects of the Achaemenid Empire to a great extent.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] They were put under much tighter control from the capital, and were heavily involved in military campaigns of the Achaemenids.
[src:maritime-timeline/achaemenid-navy] The Sidonians profited financially from the naval base stationed in their city.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] Actium belonged originally to the Corinthian colonists of Anactorium, who probably founded the sanctuary of Apollo Actius.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] In the 3rd century BC it fell to the Acarnanians, who subsequently held their religious summits there.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] There was also an ancient festival named Actia, celebrated here in honour of the god.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] Augustus after his victory enlarged the temple, and revived the ancient festival, which was henceforth celebrated once in five years (πενταετηρίς, ludi quinquennales), with musical and gymnastic contests, and horse races.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] We learn from a Greek inscription found on the site of Actium, and which is probably prior to the time of Augustus, that the chief priest of the temple was called Ἱεραπόλος, and that his name was employed in official documents, like that of the first Archon at Athens, to mark the date.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] Strabo says that the temple was situated on an eminence, and that below was a plain with a grove of trees, and a dock-yard; and in another passage he describes the harbour as situated outside of the gulf.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] On the opposite coast of Epirus, Augustus founded the city of Nicopolis in honour of his victory.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] After the foundation of Nicopolis, a few buildings sprang up around the temple, and it served as a kind of suburb to Nicopolis.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] On October 8, 1980, the Greek Ministry of Transport and Communications reported that shipwrecks from the Battle of Actium had been located at Actium near the entrance to the Ambracan Gulf.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] In Summer 2009, archaeologists discovered the ruins of the Temple of Apollo and found two statue heads, one of Apollo, one of Artemis (Diana).
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] The peninsula is connected via an underwater tunnel to the city of Preveza in Epirus, on the opposite side of the mouth of the Ambracian Gulf.
[src:maritime-timeline/actium] The total length of the tunnel is 1,570 metres (5,150 ft), of which 909 metres (2,982 ft) are located underwater.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL was at one point the most recognized brand on the Web in the United States.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL once provided a dial-up Internet service to millions of Americans and pioneered instant messaging and chat rooms with AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 1998, AOL purchased Netscape for US$4.2 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] By 2000, AOL was providing internet service to over 20 million consumers, dominating the market of internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2001, at the height of its popularity, it purchased the media conglomerate Time Warner in the largest merger in US history.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL shrank rapidly thereafter, partly due to the decline of dial-up and rise of broadband.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL was spun off from Time Warner in 2009, with Tim Armstrong appointed the new CEO.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Under his leadership, the company invested in media brands and advertising technologies.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2015, AOL was acquired by Verizon Communications for $4.4 billion, and was merged with Yahoo! the following year after the latter was also acquired by Verizon.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In May 2021, Verizon announced it would sell Verizon Media (and thus AOL) to private equity firm Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, and the sale was completed at the end of August.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In October 2025, Apollo reached a $1.5 billion deal to sell AOL to the Italian conglomerate Bending Spoons.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL began in 1983, as a short-lived venture called **Control Video Corporation** (**CVC**), founded by William von Meister.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Its sole product was an online service called GameLine for the Atari 2600 video game console, after von Meister's idea of buying music on demand was rejected by Warner Communications.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Subscribers bought a modem from the company for $49.95 and paid a one-time $15 setup fee.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] GameLine permitted subscribers to temporarily download games and keep track of high scores, at a cost of $1 per game.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The telephone disconnected and the downloaded game would remain in GameLine's Master Module, playable until the user turned off the console or downloaded another game.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In January 1983, Steve Case was hired as a marketing consultant for Control Video on the recommendation of his brother, investment banker Dan Case.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In May 1983, Jim Kimsey became a manufacturing consultant for Control Video, which was near bankruptcy.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Kimsey was brought in by his West Point friend Frank Caufield, an investor in the company.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In early 1985, von Meister left the company.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On May 24, 1985, **Quantum Computer Services**, an online services company, was founded by Kimsey from the remnants of Control Video, with Kimsey as chief executive officer and Marc Seriff as chief technology officer.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The technical team consisted of Seriff, Tom Ralston, Ray Heinrich, Steve Trus, Ken Huntsman, Janet Hunter, Dave Brown, Craig Dykstra, Doug Coward, and Mike Ficco.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 1987, Case was promoted again to executive vice-president.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Kimsey soon began to groom Case to take over the role of CEO, which he did when Kimsey retired in 1991.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Kimsey changed the company's strategy, and in 1985, launched a dedicated online service for Commodore 64 and 128 computers, originally called Quantum Link ("Q-Link" for short).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The Quantum Link software was based on software licensed from PlayNet, Inc., which was founded in 1983 by Howard Goldberg and Dave Panzl.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The service was different from other online services as it used the computing power of the Commodore 64 and the Apple II rather than just a "dumb" terminal.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] It passed tokens back and forth and provided a fixed-price service tailored for home users.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In May 1988, Quantum and Apple launched AppleLink Personal Edition for Apple II and Macintosh computers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In August 1988, Quantum launched PC Link, a service for IBM-compatible PCs developed in a joint venture with the Tandy Corporation.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] After the company parted ways with Apple in October 1989, Quantum changed the service's name to America Online.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Case promoted and sold AOL as the online service for people unfamiliar with computers, in contrast to CompuServe, which was well established in the technical community.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] From the beginning, AOL included online games in its mix of products; many classic and casual games were included in the original PlayNet software system.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In February 1991, AOL for IBM PC compatibles running MS-DOS was launched using a GeoWorks interface; it was followed a year later by AOL for Windows 3.0.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This coincided with growth in pay-based online services, like Prodigy, CompuServe, and GEnie.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] During the early 1990s, the average subscription lasted for about 25 months and accounted for $350 in total revenue.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Advertisements invited modem owners to "Try America Online FREE", promising free software and trial membership.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL discontinued Q-Link and PC Link in late 1994.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In September 1993, AOL added Usenet access to its features.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This is commonly referred to as the "Eternal September", as Usenet's cycle of new users was previously dominated by smaller numbers of college and university freshmen gaining access in September and taking a few weeks to acclimate.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This also coincided with a new "carpet bombing" marketing campaign by CMO Jan Brandt to distribute as many free trial AOL trial disks as possible through nonconventional distribution partners.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] At one point, 50% of the CDs produced worldwide had an AOL logo.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL quickly surpassed GEnie, and by the mid-1990s, it passed Prodigy (which for several years allowed AOL advertising) and CompuServe.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In November 1994, AOL purchased Booklink for its web browser, to give its users web access.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 1996, AOL replaced Booklink with a browser based on Internet Explorer, reportedly in exchange for inclusion of AOL in Windows.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL purchased search engine WebCrawler in 1995, but sold it to Excite the following year; the deal made Excite the sole search and directory service on AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] After the deal closed in March 1997, AOL launched its own branded search engine, based on Excite, called NetFind.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL charged its users an hourly fee until December 1996, when the company changed to a flat monthly rate of $19.95.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] During this time, AOL connections were flooded with users trying to connect, and many canceled their accounts due to constant busy signals.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] A commercial was made featuring Steve Case telling people AOL was working day and night to fix the problem.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Within three years, AOL's user base grew to 10 million people.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 1995, AOL was headquartered at 8619 Westwood Center Drive in the Tysons Corner CDP in unincorporated Fairfax County, Virginia in the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area. near the Town of Vienna.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL was quickly running out of room in October 1996 for its network at the Fairfax County campus.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In mid-1996, AOL moved to 22000 AOL Way in Dulles, unincorporated Loudoun County, Virginia to provide room for future growth.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In a five-year landmark agreement with the most popular operating system, AOL was bundled with Windows software.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On March 31, 1996, the short-lived eWorld was purchased by AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 1997, about half of all US homes with Internet access had it through AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] During this time, AOL's content channels, under Jason Seiken, including News, Sports, and Entertainment, experienced their greatest growth as AOL become the dominant online service internationally with more than 34 million subscribers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On August 7, 1996, AOL experienced a total outage starting at 1:00 AM PST that would last nineteen hours and took over six million people offline.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In February 1998, AOL acquired CompuServe Interactive Services (CIS) via WorldCom (later Verizon), which kept Compuware's networking business.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In November 1998, AOL announced it would acquire Netscape, best known for their web browser, in a major $4.2 billion deal.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Another large acquisition in December 1999 was that of MapQuest, for $1.1 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In January 2000, as new broadband technologies were being rolled out around the New York City metropolitan area and elsewhere across the United States, AOL and Time Warner announced plans to merge, forming AOL Time Warner, Inc.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The terms of the deal called for AOL shareholders to own 55% of the new, combined company.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The new company was led by executives from AOL, SBI, and Time Warner.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Gerald Levin, who had served as CEO of Time Warner, was CEO of the new company.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Michael Kelly (from AOL) was the chief financial officer, Robert W.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Pittman (from AOL) and Dick Parsons (from Time Warner) served as co-chief operating officers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2002, Jonathan Miller became CEO of AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The following year, AOL Time Warner dropped the "AOL" from its name.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] It was the largest merger in history when completed with the combined value of the companies at $360 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This value fell sharply, to as low as $120 billion, as markets repriced AOL's valuation as a pure internet firm more modestly when combined with the traditional media and cable business.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This status did not last long, and the company's value rose again within three months.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] By the end of that year, the tide had turned against "pure" internet companies, with many collapsing under falling stock prices, and even the strongest companies in the field losing up to 75% of their market value.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The decline continued through 2001, but even with the losses, AOL was among the internet giants that continued to outperform brick and mortar companies.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2004, along with the launch of AOL 9.0 Optimized, AOL also made available the option of personalized greetings which would enable the user to hear his or her name while accessing basic functions and mail alerts, or while logging in or out.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2005, AOL broadcast the Live 8 concert live over the Internet, and thousands of users downloaded clips of the concert over the following months.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In late 2005, AOL released AOL Safety & Security Center, a bundle of McAfee Antivirus, CA anti-spyware, and proprietary firewall and phishing protection software.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] News reports in late 2005 identified companies such as Yahoo!, Microsoft, and Google as candidates for turning AOL into a joint venture.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Those plans were abandoned when it was revealed on December 20, 2005, that Google would purchase a 5% share of AOL for $1 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On April 3, 2006, AOL announced that it would retire the full name America Online.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The official name of the service became AOL, and the full name of the Time Warner subdivision became AOL LLC.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On June 8, 2006, AOL offered a new program called AOL Active Security Monitor, a diagnostic tool to monitor and rate PC security status, and recommended additional security software from AOL or Download.com.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Two months later, AOL released AOL Active Virus Shield, a free product developed by Kaspersky Lab, that did not require an AOL account, only an internet email address.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The ISP side of AOL UK was bought by Carphone Warehouse in October 2006 to take advantage of its 100,000 LLU customers, making Carphone Warehouse the largest LLU provider in the UK.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In August 2006, AOL announced that it would offer email accounts and software previously available only to its paying customers, provided that users accessed AOL or AOL.com through an access method not owned by AOL (otherwise known as "third party transit", "bring your own access" or "BYOA").
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The move was designed to reduce costs associated with the "walled garden" business model by reducing usage of AOL-owned access points and shifting members with high-speed internet access from client-based usage to the more lucrative advertising provider AOL.com.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The change from paid to free access was also designed to slow the rate at which members canceled their accounts and defected to Microsoft Hotmail, Yahoo! or other free email providers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Also in August, AOL informed its US customers of an increase in the price of its dial-up access to $25.90.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The increase was part of an effort to migrate the service's remaining dial-up users to broadband, as the increased price was the same as that of its monthly DSL access.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] However, AOL subsequently began offering unlimited dial-up access for $9.95 a month.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On November 16, 2006, Randy Falco succeeded Jonathan Miller as CEO.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In December 2006, AOL closed its last remaining call center in the United States, "taking the America out of America Online," according to industry pundits.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Service centers based in India and the Philippines continue to provide customer support and technical assistance to subscribers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On September 17, 2007, AOL announced the relocation of one of its corporate headquarters from Dulles, Virginia to New York City and the combination of its advertising units into a new subsidiary called Platform A.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This action followed several advertising acquisitions, most notably Advertising.com, and highlighted the company's new focus on advertising-driven business models.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL management stressed that "significant operations" would remain in Dulles, which included the company's access services and modem banks.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In October 2007, AOL announced the relocation of its other headquarters from Loudoun County, Virginia to New York City, while continuing to operate its Virginia offices.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] As part of the move to New York and the restructuring of responsibilities at the Dulles headquarters complex after the Reston move, Falco announced on October 15, 2007, plans to lay off 2,000 employees worldwide by the end of 2007, beginning "immediately".
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The result was a layoff of approximately 40% of AOL's employees.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Most compensation packages associated with the October 2007 layoffs included a minimum of 120 days of severance pay, 60 of which were offered in lieu of the 60-day advance notice requirement by provisions of the 1988 federal WARN Act.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] By November 2007, AOL's customer base had been reduced to 10.1 million subscribers, slightly more than the number of subscribers of Comcast and AT&T Yahoo!.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] According to Falco, as of December 2007, the conversion rate of accounts from paid access to free access was more than 80%.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On January 3, 2008, AOL announced the closing of its Reston, Virginia, data center, which was sold to CRG West.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On February 6, Time Warner CEO Jeff Bewkes announced that Time Warner would divide AOL's internet-access and advertising businesses, with the possibility of later selling the internet-access division.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On March 13, 2008, AOL purchased the social networking site Bebo for $850 million (£417 million).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On July 25, AOL announced that it was shuttering Xdrive, AOL Pictures and BlueString to save on costs and focus on its core advertising business.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On October 31, AOL Hometown (a web-hosting service for the websites of AOL customers) and the AOL Journal blog hosting service were eliminated.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On March 12, 2009, Tim Armstrong, formerly with Google, was named chairman and CEO of AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On May 28, Time Warner announced that it would position AOL as an independent company after Google's shares ceased at the end of the fiscal year.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On November 23, AOL unveiled a new brand identity with the wordmark "Aol." superimposed onto canvases created by commissioned artists.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The new identity, designed by Wolff Olins, was integrated with all of AOL's services on December 10, the date upon which AOL traded independently for the first time since the Time Warner merger on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On April 6, 2010, AOL announced plans to shutter or sell Bebo.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On June 16, the property was sold to Criterion Capital Partners for an undisclosed amount, believed to be approximately $10 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In December, AIM eliminated access to AOL chat rooms, noting a marked decline in usage in recent months.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Under Armstrong's leadership, AOL followed a new business direction marked by a series of acquisitions.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] It announced the acquisition of Patch Media, a network of community-specific news and information sites focused on towns and communities.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On September 28, 2010, at the San Francisco TechCrunch Disrupt Conference, AOL signed an agreement to acquire TechCrunch.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On December 12, 2010, AOL acquired about.me, a personal profile and identity platform, four days after the platform's public launch.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On January 31, 2011, AOL announced the acquisition of European video distribution network goviral.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In March 2011, AOL acquired *HuffPost* for $315 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Shortly after the acquisition was announced, *Huffington Post* co-founder Arianna Huffington replaced AOL content chief David Eun, assuming the role of president and editor-in-chief of the AOL Huffington Post Media Group.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On March 10, AOL announced that it would cut approximately 900 workers following the *HuffPost* acquisition.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On September 14, 2011, AOL formed a strategic ad-selling partnership with two of its largest competitors, Yahoo and Microsoft.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The three companies would begin selling inventory on each other's sites.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The strategy was designed to help the companies compete with Google and advertising networks.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On February 28, 2012, AOL partnered with PBS to launch MAKERS, a digital documentary series focusing on high-achieving women in industries perceived as male-dominated such as war, comedy, space, business, Hollywood and politics.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Subjects for MAKERS episodes have included Oprah Winfrey, Hillary Clinton, Sheryl Sandberg, Martha Stewart, Indra Nooyi, Lena Dunham and Ellen DeGeneres.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On March 15, 2012, AOL announced the acquisition of Hipster, a mobile photo-sharing app, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On April 9, 2012, AOL announced a deal to sell 800 patents to Microsoft for $1.056 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The deal included a perpetual license for AOL to use the patents.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In April, AOL took several steps to expand its ability to generate revenue through online video advertising.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The company announced that it would offer gross rating point (GRP) guarantee for online video, mirroring the television-ratings system and guaranteeing audience delivery for online-video advertising campaigns bought across its properties.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This announcement came just days before the Digital Content NewFront (DCNF) a two-week event held by AOL, Google, Hulu, Microsoft, Vevo and Yahoo to showcase the participating sites' digital video offerings.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The DCNF was conducted in advance of the traditional television upfronts in the hope of diverting more advertising money into the digital space.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On April 24, the company launched the AOL On network, a single website for its video output.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In February 2013, AOL reported its fourth quarter revenue of $599.5 million, its first growth in quarterly revenue in eight years.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In August 2013, Armstrong announced that Patch Media would scale back or sell hundreds of its local news sites.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Not long afterward, layoffs began, with up to 500 out of 1,100 positions initially impacted.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On January 15, 2014, Patch Media was spun off, and majority ownership was held by Hale Global.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] By the end of 2014, AOL controlled 0.74% of the global advertising market, well behind industry leader Google's 31.4%.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On January 23, 2014, AOL acquired Gravity, a software startup that tracked users' online behavior and tailored ads and content based on their interests, for $83 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The deal, which included approximately 40 Gravity employees and the company's personalization technology, was Armstrong's fourth-largest deal since taking command in 2009.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Later that year, AOL acquired Vidible, a company that developed technology to help websites run video content from other publishers, and help video publishers sell their content to these websites.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The deal, which was announced December 1, 2014, was reportedly worth roughly $50 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On July 16, 2014, AOL earned an Emmy nomination for the AOL original series *The Future Starts Here* in the News and Documentary category.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This came days after AOL earned its first Primetime Emmy Award nomination and win for *Park Bench with Steve Buscemi* in the Outstanding Short Form Variety Series.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Created and hosted by Tiffany Shlain, the series focused on humans' relationship with technology and featured episodes such as "The Future of Our Species", "Why We Love Robots" and "A Case for Optimism".
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On May 12, 2015, Verizon announced plans to buy AOL for $50 per share in a deal valued at $4.4 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The transaction was completed on June 23.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Armstrong, who continued to lead the firm following regulatory approval, called the deal the logical next step for AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] "If you look forward five years, you're going to be in a space where there are going to be massive, global-scale networks, and there's no better partner for us to go forward with than Verizon." he said.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] "It's really not about selling the company today.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Analyst David Bank said he thought the deal made sense for Verizon.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The deal will broaden Verizon's advertising sales platforms and increase its video production ability through websites such as *HuffPost*, TechCrunch, and Engadget.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] However, Craig Moffett said it was unlikely the deal would make a big difference to Verizon's bottom line.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL had about two million dial-up subscribers at the time of the buyout.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The announcement caused AOL's stock price to rise 17%, while Verizon's stock price dropped slightly.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Shortly before the Verizon purchase, on April 14, 2015, AOL launched ONE by AOL, a digital marketing programmatic platform that unifies buying channels and audience management platforms to track and optimize campaigns over multiple screens.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Later that year, on September 15, AOL expanded the product with ONE by AOL: Creative, which is geared towards creative and media agencies to similarly connect marketing and ad distribution efforts.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On May 8, 2015, AOL reported its first-quarter revenue of $625.1 million, $483.5 million of which came from advertising and related operations, marking a 7% increase from Q1 2014.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Over that year, the AOL Platforms division saw a 21% increase in revenue, but a drop in adjusted OIBDA due to increased investments in the company's video and programmatic platforms.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On June 29, 2015, AOL announced a deal with Microsoft to take over the majority of its digital advertising business.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Under the pact, as many as 1,200 Microsoft employees involved with the business will be transferred to AOL, and the company will take over the sale of display, video, and mobile ads on various Microsoft platforms in nine countries, including Brazil, Canada, the United States, and the United Kingdom.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Additionally, Google Search will be replaced on AOL properties with Bing—which will display advertising sold by Microsoft.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Both advertising deals are subject to affiliate marketing revenue sharing.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On September 3, 2015, AOL agreed to buy Millennial Media for $238 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On October 23, 2015, AOL completed the acquisition.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On October 1, 2015, Go90, a free ad-supported mobile video service aimed at young adult and teen viewers that Verizon owns and AOL oversees and operates, launched its content publicly after months of beta testing.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The initial launch line-up included content from Comedy Central, HuffPost, Nerdist News, Univision News, Vice, ESPN and MTV.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On April 20, 2016, AOL acquired virtual reality studio RYOT to bring immersive 360 degree video and VR content to HuffPost's global audience across desktop, mobile, and apps.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In July 2016, Verizon Communications announced its intent to purchase the core internet business of Yahoo!.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Verizon merged AOL with Yahoo into a new company called "Oath Inc.", which in January 2019 rebranded itself as Verizon Media.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In April 2018, Oath Inc. sold Moviefone to MoviePass Parent Helios and Matheson Analytics.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In November 2020 the *Huffington Post* was sold to BuzzFeed in a stock deal.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On May 3, 2021, Verizon announced it would sell 90 percent of its Verizon Media division to Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, becoming the second independent incarnation of Yahoo Inc.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2025, AOL ended its dial-up internet service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In October 2025, Bending Spoons acquired AOL in a deal valued at roughly $1.5 billion.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In a statement, Bending Spoons CEO Luca Ferrari cited AOL's 30 million active users as part of what made the property attractive.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The purchase was quietly completed in January 2026, Bending Spoons then laid off more than 100 AOL employees in February 2026.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL's web ecosystem operates primarily as a content aggregator and digital service portal.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The AOL homepage aggregates news, lifestyle, and entertainment content from major syndicated third-party media wires and partner networks.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In addition to mobile-optimized web experiences, AOL produces mobile applications for its remaining properties and standalone software utilities.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL Mail is AOL's proprietary email client.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] It provides fully integrated webmail services and direct links to news headlines on AOL content sites.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL Plans offers multiple online safety and assistance subscription bundles: identity theft protection, data security tools, and a general online technical assistance service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] In 2017, a paid internet suite version called AOL Desktop Gold was released, available for $4.99 per month after a trial period.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] It replaced the previous free software tier.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On January 10, 2018, all versions of the original AOL Desktop were shut down so AOL could focus towards AOL Desktop Gold and AOL Shield.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Following the shutdown of AIM, AOL's original legacy chat rooms continued to be accessible through AOL Desktop Gold until the chat system was permanently shut down on December 15, 2020.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] When it owned the Huffington Post, AOL's content ecosystem featured contributors consisting of over 20,000 bloggers, including politicians, celebrities, academics, and policy experts, who contributed on a wide range of topics.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Several major media brands formerly owned by AOL—including Engadget, Autoblog, TechCrunch, and Built by Girls—became part of Verizon Media (now Yahoo) following Verizon's acquisition of AOL in 2015.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Mobile applications and experimental products associated with these eras, such as Alto, Pip, and Vivv, have also been retired.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL previously operated a global portfolio of advertising technologies and services.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] This included data and programmatic solutions handled through its proprietary ad technology stack, ONE by AOL, which was built on acquisitions such as AdapTV (2013), Convertro (2014), Precision Demand (2014), and Vidible (2014).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] ONE by AOL operated under two separate banners: ONE by AOL for Publishers and ONE by AOL for Advertisers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] On September 10, 2018, parent company Oath consolidated BrightRoll, One by AOL, and Yahoo Gemini into a unified ad-tech platform named Oath Ad Platforms, which was later rebranded as Yahoo!
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL originally built its user base on Dial-up Internet access.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] While the service retained 2.1 million subscribers in 2015, membership plummeted to a few thousand by 2021 as remaining premium users transitioned to software support packages.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL officially discontinued its legacy dial-up service on September 30, 2025.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) was AOL's flagship proprietary instant-messaging tool launched in 1997.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] At its peak, billions of messages were sent daily across AIM and associated AOL chat properties.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Over time, it lost significant market share to competitors like Google Chat, Facebook Messenger, and text messaging.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] It also included a integrated video-chat tool, AV by AIM.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] AOL discontinued the AIM service on December 15, 2017.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Subsequent iterations shifted back to supporting the 9.X version lines.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Version 9.8 replaced existing Internet Explorer engine dependencies with the CEF engine to mimic modern web-browsing frameworks like Google Chrome.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Version 11 introduced a complete software architecture rewrite while preserving the 9.8 legacy layout.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The freeware software stack was fully deprecated in 2017 in favor of the paid subscription iteration, AOL Desktop Gold.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] Separately, the company maintained the **AOL Toolbar**, a web browser toolbar distributed as a Mozilla plug-in offering immediate web hooks into fundamental AOL platforms.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p01] The toolbar utility was maintained from 2007 until its retirement in 2018.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In its earlier incarnation as a "walled garden" community and service provider, AOL received criticism for its community policies, terms of service, and customer service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL was known for its direct mailing of CD-ROMs and 3.5-inch floppy disks containing its software.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The disks were distributed in large numbers; at one point, half of the CDs manufactured worldwide had AOL logos on them.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The marketing tactic was criticized for its environmental cost, and AOL CDs were recognized as *PC World*'s most annoying tech product.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL used a system of volunteers to moderate its chat rooms, forums and user communities.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The program dated back to AOL's early days, when it charged by the hour for access and one of its highest billing services was chat.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL provided free access to community leaders in exchange for moderating the chat rooms, and this effectively made chat very cheap to operate, and more lucrative than AOL's other services of the era.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] There were 33,000 community leaders in 1996.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] All community leaders received hours of training and underwent a probationary period.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] While most community leaders moderated chat rooms, some ran AOL communities and controlled their layout and design, with as much as 90% of AOL's content being created or overseen by community managers until 1996.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] By 1996, ISPs were beginning to charge flat rates for unlimited access, which they could do at a profit because they only provided internet access.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Even though AOL would lose money with such a pricing scheme, it was forced by market conditions to offer unlimited access in October 1996.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In order to return to profitability, AOL rapidly shifted its focus from content creation to advertising, resulting in less of a need to carefully moderate every forum and chat room to keep users willing to pay by the minute to remain connected.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] After unlimited access, AOL considered scrapping the program entirely, but continued it with a reduced number of community leaders, with scaled-back roles in creating content.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Although community leaders continued to receive free access, after 1996 they were motivated more by the prestige of the position and the access to moderator tools and restricted areas within AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] By 1999, there were over 15,000 volunteers in the program.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In May 1999, two former volunteers filed a class-action lawsuit alleging AOL violated the Fair Labor Standards Act by treating volunteers like employees.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Volunteers had to apply for the position, commit to working for at least three to four hours a week, fill out timecards and sign a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On July 22, AOL ended its youth corps, which consisted of 350 underage community leaders.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] At this time, the United States Department of Labor began an investigation into the program, but it came to no conclusions about AOL's practices.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL ended its community leader program on June 8, 2005.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The class action lawsuit dragged on for years, even after AOL ended the program and AOL declined as a major internet company.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In 2010, AOL finally agreed to settle the lawsuit for $15 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The community leader program was described as an example of co-production in a 2009 article in *International Journal of Cultural Studies*.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL has faced a number of lawsuits over claims that it has been slow to stop billing customers after their accounts have been canceled, either by the company or the user.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In addition, AOL changed its method of calculating used minutes in response to a class action lawsuit.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Previously, AOL would add 15 seconds to the time a user was connected to the service and round up to the next whole minute (thus, a person who used the service for 12 minutes and 46 seconds would be charged for 14 minutes).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL claimed this was to account for sign on/sign off time, but because this practice was not made known to its customers, the plaintiffs won (some also pointed out that signing on and off did not always take 15 seconds, especially when connecting via another ISP).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL disclosed its connection-time calculation methods to all of its customers and credited them with extra free hours.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In addition, the AOL software would notify the user of exactly how long they were connected and how many minutes they were being charged.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL was sued by the Ohio Attorney General in October 2003 for improper billing practices.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL agreed to resolve any consumer complaints filed with the Ohio AG's office.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In December 2006, AOL agreed to provide restitution to Florida consumers to settle the case filed against them by the Florida Attorney General.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Many customers complained that AOL personnel ignored their demands to cancel service and stop billing.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In response to approximately 300 consumer complaints, the New York Attorney General's office began an inquiry of AOL's customer service policies.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The investigation revealed that the company had an elaborate scheme for rewarding employees who purported to retain or "save" subscribers who had called to cancel their Internet service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In many instances, such retention was done against subscribers' wishes, or without their consent.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Under the scheme, customer service personnel received bonuses worth tens of thousands of dollars if they could successfully dissuade or "save" half of the people who called to cancel service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] For several years, AOL had instituted minimum retention or "save" percentages, which consumer representatives were expected to meet.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] These bonuses, and the minimum "save" rates accompanying them, had the effect of employees not honoring cancellations, or otherwise making cancellation unduly difficult for consumers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On August 24, 2005, America Online agreed to pay $1.25 million to the state of New York and reformed its customer service procedures.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Under the agreement, AOL would no longer require its customer service representatives to meet a minimum quota for customer retention in order to receive a bonus.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] However the agreement only covered people in the state of New York.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On June 13, 2006, Vincent Ferrari documented his account cancellation phone call in a blog post, stating he had switched to broadband years earlier.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In the recorded phone call, the AOL representative refused to cancel the account unless the 30-year-old Ferrari explained why AOL hours were still being recorded on it.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Ferrari insisted that AOL software was not even installed on the computer.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] When Ferrari demanded that the account be canceled regardless, the AOL representative asked to speak with Ferrari's father, for whom the account had been set up.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] When CNBC reporters tried to have an account on AOL cancelled, they were hung up on immediately and it ultimately took more than 45 minutes to cancel the account.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On July 19, 2006, AOL's entire retention manual was released on the Internet.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On August 3, 2006, Time Warner announced that the company would be dissolving AOL's retention centers due to its profits hinging on $1 billion in cost cuts.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The company estimated that it would lose more than six million subscribers over the following year.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL often sent unsolicited mass direct mail of 31⁄2" floppy disks and CD-ROMs containing their software.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] They were the most frequent user of this marketing tactic, and received criticism for the environmental cost of the campaign.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] According to *PC World*, in the 1990s "you couldn't open a magazine (*PC World* included) or your mailbox without an AOL disk falling out of it".
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The mass distribution of these disks was seen as wasteful by the public and led to protest groups.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] One such was No More AOL CDs, a web-based effort by two IT workers to collect one million disks with the intent to return the disks to AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The website was started in August 2001, and an estimated 410,176 CDs were collected by August 2007 when the project was shut down.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In 2000, AOL was served with an $8 billion lawsuit alleging that its AOL 5.0 software caused significant difficulties for users attempting to use third-party Internet service providers.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The lawsuit sought damages of up to $1000 for each user that had downloaded the software cited at the time of the lawsuit.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL later agreed to a settlement of $15 million, without admission of wrongdoing.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The AOL software then was given a feature called AOL Dialer, or AOL Connect on Mac OS X.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] This feature allowed users to connect to the ISP without running the full interface.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] This allowed users to use only the applications they wish to use, especially if they do not favor the AOL Browser.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL 9.0 was once identified by Stopbadware as being *under investigation* for installing additional software without disclosure, and modifying browser preferences, toolbars, and icons.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] However, as of the release of AOL 9.0 VR (Vista Ready) on January 26, 2007, it was no longer considered badware due to changes AOL made in the software.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] When AOL gave clients access to Usenet in 1993, they hid at least one newsgroup in standard list view: *alt.aol-sucks*.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL did list the newsgroup in the alternative description view, but changed the description to "Flames and complaints about America Online".
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] With AOL clients swarming Usenet newsgroups, the old, existing user base started to develop a strong distaste for both AOL and its clients, referring to the new state of affairs as Eternal September.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL discontinued access to Usenet on June 25, 2005.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] No official details were provided as to the cause of decommissioning Usenet access, except providing users the suggestion to access Usenet services from a third-party, Google Groups.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL then provided community-based message boards in lieu of Usenet.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL has a detailed set of guidelines and expectations for users on their service, known as the Terms of Service (TOS, also known as Conditions of Service (COS) in the UK).
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] It is separated into three different sections: *Member Agreement*, *Community Guidelines* and *Privacy Policy*.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] All three agreements are presented to users at time of registration and digital acceptance is achieved when they access the AOL service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] During the period when volunteer chat room hosts and board monitors were used, chat room hosts were given a brief online training session and test on Terms of Service violations.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] There have been many complaints over rules that govern an AOL user's conduct.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Some users disagree with the TOS, citing the guidelines are too strict to follow coupled with the fact the TOS may change without users being made aware.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] A considerable cause for this was likely due to alleged censorship of user-generated content during the earlier years of growth for AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] This decision drew fire from MoveOn, which characterized the program as an "email tax", and the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), which characterized it as a shakedown of non-profits.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] A website called Dearaol.com was launched, with an online petition and a blog that garnered hundreds of signatures from people and organizations expressing their opposition to AOL's use of Goodmail.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Esther Dyson defended the move in an editorial in *The New York Times*, saying "I hope Goodmail succeeds, and that it has lots of competition.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] I also think it and its competitors will eventually transform into services that more directly serve the interests of mail recipients.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Tim Lee of the Technology Liberation Front posted an article that questioned the Electronic Frontier Foundation's adopting a confrontational posture when dealing with private companies.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] SpamAssassin developer Justin Mason posted some criticism of the EFF's and Moveon's "going overboard" in their opposition to the scheme.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The dearaol.com campaign lost momentum and disappeared, with the last post to the now defunct dearaol.com blog—"AOL starts the shakedown" being made on May 9, 2006.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Comcast, who also used the service, announced on its website that Goodmail had ceased operations and as of February 4, 2011, they no longer used the service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On August 4, 2006, AOL released a compressed text file on one of its websites containing 20 million search keywords for over 650,000 users over a three-month period between March 1 and May 31, 2006, intended for research purposes.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL pulled the file from public access by August 7, but not before its wide distribution on the Internet by others.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Derivative research, titled *A Picture of Search*, was published by authors Pass, Chowdhury and Torgeson for The First International Conference on Scalable Information Systems.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The data were used by websites such as AOLstalker for entertainment purposes, where users of AOLstalker are encouraged to judge AOL clients based on the humorousness of personal details revealed by search behavior.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] In 2003, Jason Smathers, an AOL employee, was convicted of stealing America Online's 92 million screen names and selling them to a known spammer.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to conspiracy charges in 2005.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to violations of the US CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] He was sentenced in August 2005 to 15 months in prison; the sentencing judge also recommended Smathers be forced to pay $84,000 in restitution, triple the $28,000 that he sold the addresses for.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] On February 27, 2012, a class action lawsuit was filed against Support.com, Inc. and partner AOL, Inc.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] The companies then offered to sell software—for which AOL allegedly charged $4.99 a month and Support.com $29—to remedy those problems.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Both AOL, Inc. and Support.com, Inc. settled on May 30, 2013, for $8.5 million.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] This included $25.00 to each valid class member and $100,000 each to Consumer Watchdog and the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL continues to market Computer Checkup.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including AOL.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] According to leaks of said program, AOL joined the PRISM program in 2011.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] At one time, most AOL users had an online "profile" hosted by the AOL Hometown service.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] When AOL Hometown was discontinued, users had to create a new profile on Bebo.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] This was an unsuccessful attempt to create a social network that would compete with Facebook.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] When the value of Bebo decreased to a tiny fraction of the $850 million AOL paid for it, users were forced to recreate their profiles yet again, on a new service called AOL Lifestream.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] AOL decided to shut down Lifestream on February 24, 2017, and gave users one month's notice to save photos and videos that had been uploaded to Lifestream.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] Following the shutdown, AOL no longer provides any option for hosting user profiles.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] During the Hometown/Bebo/Lifestream era, another user's profile could be displayed by clicking the "Buddy Info" button in the AOL Desktop software.
[src:maritime-timeline/aol-p02] After the shutdown of Lifestream, this was no longer supported, but opened to the AIM home page (www.aim.com), which also became defunct, redirecting to AOL's home page.
[src:maritime-timeline/maritime-timeline] This is a timeline of events in maritime history.
